{"cues": [{"duration": 4.82, "start": 4.06, "text": "Here, we tackle backpropagation, the core algorithm behind how neural networks learn."}, {"duration": 3.979, "start": 9.4, "text": "After a quick recap for where we are, the first thing I'll do is an intuitive walkthrough"}, {"duration": 3.621, "start": 13.379, "text": "for what the algorithm is actually doing, without any reference to the formulas."}, {"duration": 2.634, "start": 17.66, "text": "Then, for those of you who do want to dive into the math,"}, {"duration": 2.726, "start": 20.294, "text": "the next video goes into the calculus underlying all this."}, {"duration": 3.59, "start": 23.82, "text": "If you watched the last two videos, or if you're just jumping in with the appropriate"}, {"duration": 3.59, "start": 27.41, "text": "background, you know what a neural network is, and how it feeds forward information."}, {"duration": 4.327, "start": 31.68, "text": "Here, we're doing the classic example of recognizing handwritten digits whose pixel"}, {"duration": 3.597, "start": 36.007, "text": "values get fed into the first layer of the network with 784 neurons,"}, {"duration": 4.379, "start": 39.604, "text": "and I've been showing a network with two hidden layers having just 16 neurons each,"}, {"duration": 4.275, "start": 43.983, "text": "and an output layer of 10 neurons, indicating which digit the network is choosing"}, {"duration": 0.782, "start": 48.258, "text": "as its answer."}, {"duration": 2.999, "start": 50.04, "text": "I'm also expecting you to understand gradient descent,"}, {"duration": 3.777, "start": 53.039, "text": "as described in the last video, and how what we mean by learning is"}, {"duration": 4.444, "start": 56.816, "text": "that we want to find which weights and biases minimize a certain cost function."}, {"duration": 3.715, "start": 62.04, "text": "As a quick reminder, for the cost of a single training example,"}, {"duration": 4.953, "start": 65.755, "text": "you take the output the network gives, along with the output you wanted it to give,"}, {"duration": 3.892, "start": 70.708, "text": "and add up the squares of the differences between each component."}, {"duration": 3.41, "start": 75.38, "text": "Doing this for all of your tens of thousands of training examples and"}, {"duration": 3.41, "start": 78.79, "text": "averaging the results, this gives you the total cost of the network."}, {"duration": 4.071, "start": 82.2, "text": "And as if that's not enough to think about, as described in the last video,"}, {"duration": 4.396, "start": 86.271, "text": "the thing that we're looking for is the negative gradient of this cost function,"}, {"duration": 3.799, "start": 90.667, "text": "which tells you how you need to change all of the weights and biases,"}, {"duration": 3.854, "start": 94.466, "text": "all of these connections, so as to most efficiently decrease the cost."}, {"duration": 2.404, "start": 103.26, "text": "Backpropagation, the topic of this video, is an"}, {"duration": 2.916, "start": 105.664, "text": "algorithm for computing that crazy complicated gradient."}, {"duration": 3.736, "start": 109.14, "text": "And the one idea from the last video that I really want you to hold firmly"}, {"duration": 3.585, "start": 112.876, "text": "in your mind right now is that because thinking of the gradient vector"}, {"duration": 2.979, "start": 116.461, "text": "as a direction in 13,000 dimensions is, to put it lightly,"}, {"duration": 4.14, "start": 119.44, "text": "beyond the scope of our imaginations, there's another way you can think about it."}, {"duration": 3.141, "start": 124.6, "text": "The magnitude of each component here is telling you how"}, {"duration": 3.199, "start": 127.741, "text": "sensitive the cost function is to each weight and bias."}, {"duration": 3.944, "start": 131.8, "text": "For example, let's say you go through the process I'm about to describe,"}, {"duration": 4.765, "start": 135.744, "text": "and you compute the negative gradient, and the component associated with the weight on"}, {"duration": 4.765, "start": 140.509, "text": "this edge here comes out to be 3.2, while the component associated with this edge here"}, {"duration": 0.986, "start": 145.274, "text": "comes out as 0.1."}, {"duration": 4.149, "start": 146.82, "text": "The way you would interpret that is that the cost of the function is 32 times more"}, {"duration": 3.996, "start": 150.969, "text": "sensitive to changes in that first weight, so if you were to wiggle that value"}, {"duration": 3.238, "start": 154.965, "text": "just a little bit, it's going to cause some change to the cost,"}, {"duration": 3.896, "start": 158.203, "text": "and that change is 32 times greater than what the same wiggle to that second"}, {"duration": 0.961, "start": 162.099, "text": "weight would give."}, {"duration": 2.948, "start": 168.42, "text": "Personally, when I was first learning about backpropagation,"}, {"duration": 4.372, "start": 171.368, "text": "I think the most confusing aspect was just the notation and the index chasing of it all."}, {"duration": 3.224, "start": 176.22, "text": "But once you unwrap what each part of this algorithm is really doing,"}, {"duration": 3.037, "start": 179.444, "text": "each individual effect it's having is actually pretty intuitive,"}, {"duration": 4.159, "start": 182.481, "text": "it's just that there's a lot of little adjustments getting layered on top of each other."}, {"duration": 4.04, "start": 187.74, "text": "So I'm going to start things off here with a complete disregard for the notation,"}, {"duration": 4.34, "start": 191.78, "text": "and just step through the effects each training example has on the weights and biases."}, {"duration": 4.713, "start": 197.02, "text": "Because the cost function involves averaging a certain cost per example over all"}, {"duration": 4.594, "start": 201.733, "text": "the tens of thousands of training examples, the way we adjust the weights and"}, {"duration": 4.713, "start": 206.327, "text": "biases for a single gradient descent step also depends on every single example."}, {"duration": 3.851, "start": 211.68, "text": "Or rather, in principle it should, but for computational efficiency we'll do a little"}, {"duration": 3.669, "start": 215.531, "text": "trick later to keep you from needing to hit every single example for every step."}, {"duration": 3.41, "start": 219.2, "text": "In other cases, right now, all we're going to do is focus"}, {"duration": 3.35, "start": 222.61, "text": "our attention on one single example, this image of a 2."}, {"duration": 2.508, "start": 226.72, "text": "What effect should this one training example have"}, {"duration": 2.252, "start": 229.228, "text": "on how the weights and biases get adjusted?"}, {"duration": 3.533, "start": 232.68, "text": "Let's say we're at a point where the network is not well trained yet,"}, {"duration": 3.38, "start": 236.213, "text": "so the activations in the output are going to look pretty random,"}, {"duration": 2.407, "start": 239.593, "text": "maybe something like 0.5, 0.8, 0.2, on and on."}, {"duration": 2.295, "start": 242.52, "text": "We can't directly change those activations, we"}, {"duration": 2.345, "start": 244.815, "text": "only have influence on the weights and biases."}, {"duration": 2.792, "start": 247.16, "text": "But it's helpful to keep track of which adjustments"}, {"duration": 2.628, "start": 249.952, "text": "we wish should take place to that output layer."}, {"duration": 3.038, "start": 253.36, "text": "And since we want it to classify the image as a 2,"}, {"duration": 4.862, "start": 256.398, "text": "we want that third value to get nudged up while all the others get nudged down."}, {"duration": 3.636, "start": 262.06, "text": "Moreover, the sizes of these nudges should be proportional"}, {"duration": 3.824, "start": 265.696, "text": "to how far away each current value is from its target value."}, {"duration": 3.56, "start": 270.22, "text": "For example, the increase to that number 2 neuron's activation"}, {"duration": 4.077, "start": 273.78, "text": "is in a sense more important than the decrease to the number 8 neuron,"}, {"duration": 3.043, "start": 277.857, "text": "which is already pretty close to where it should be."}, {"duration": 2.944, "start": 282.04, "text": "So zooming in further, let's focus just on this one neuron,"}, {"duration": 2.296, "start": 284.984, "text": "the one whose activation we wish to increase."}, {"duration": 4.346, "start": 288.18, "text": "Remember, that activation is defined as a certain weighted sum of all the"}, {"duration": 2.858, "start": 292.526, "text": "activations in the previous layer, plus a bias,"}, {"duration": 5.001, "start": 295.384, "text": "which is all then plugged into something like the sigmoid squishification function,"}, {"duration": 0.655, "start": 300.385, "text": "or a ReLU."}, {"duration": 2.802, "start": 301.64, "text": "So there are three different avenues that can team"}, {"duration": 2.578, "start": 304.442, "text": "up together to help increase that activation."}, {"duration": 3.186, "start": 307.44, "text": "You can increase the bias, you can increase the weights,"}, {"duration": 3.414, "start": 310.626, "text": "and you can change the activations from the previous layer."}, {"duration": 2.419, "start": 314.94, "text": "Focusing on how the weights should be adjusted,"}, {"duration": 3.501, "start": 317.359, "text": "notice how the weights actually have differing levels of influence."}, {"duration": 3.756, "start": 321.44, "text": "The connections with the brightest neurons from the preceding layer have the"}, {"duration": 3.904, "start": 325.196, "text": "biggest effect since those weights are multiplied by larger activation values."}, {"duration": 2.424, "start": 331.46, "text": "So if you were to increase one of those weights,"}, {"duration": 4.192, "start": 333.884, "text": "it actually has a stronger influence on the ultimate cost function than increasing"}, {"duration": 2.424, "start": 338.076, "text": "the weights of connections with dimmer neurons,"}, {"duration": 2.98, "start": 340.5, "text": "at least as far as this one training example is concerned."}, {"duration": 2.165, "start": 344.42, "text": "Remember, when we talk about gradient descent,"}, {"duration": 3.67, "start": 346.585, "text": "we don't just care about whether each component should get nudged up or down,"}, {"duration": 2.965, "start": 350.255, "text": "we care about which ones give you the most bang for your buck."}, {"duration": 3.491, "start": 355.02, "text": "This, by the way, is at least somewhat reminiscent of a theory in"}, {"duration": 4.028, "start": 358.511, "text": "neuroscience for how biological networks of neurons learn, Hebbian theory,"}, {"duration": 3.921, "start": 362.539, "text": "often summed up in the phrase, neurons that fire together wire together."}, {"duration": 4.459, "start": 367.26, "text": "Here, the biggest increases to weights, the biggest strengthening of connections,"}, {"duration": 2.808, "start": 371.719, "text": "happens between neurons which are the most active,"}, {"duration": 2.753, "start": 374.527, "text": "and the ones which we wish to become more active."}, {"duration": 3.216, "start": 377.94, "text": "In a sense, the neurons that are firing while seeing a 2 get"}, {"duration": 3.324, "start": 381.156, "text": "more strongly linked to those firing when thinking about a 2."}, {"duration": 3.956, "start": 385.4, "text": "To be clear, I'm not in a position to make statements one way or another about"}, {"duration": 4.006, "start": 389.356, "text": "whether artificial networks of neurons behave anything like biological brains,"}, {"duration": 4.311, "start": 393.362, "text": "and this fires together wire together idea comes with a couple meaningful asterisks,"}, {"duration": 3.347, "start": 397.673, "text": "but taken as a very loose analogy, I find it interesting to note."}, {"duration": 3.806, "start": 401.94, "text": "Anyway, the third way we can help increase this neuron's activation"}, {"duration": 3.294, "start": 405.746, "text": "is by changing all the activations in the previous layer."}, {"duration": 3.975, "start": 409.04, "text": "Namely, if everything connected to that digit 2 neuron with a positive"}, {"duration": 4.769, "start": 413.015, "text": "weight got brighter, and if everything connected with a negative weight got dimmer,"}, {"duration": 2.896, "start": 417.784, "text": "then that digit 2 neuron would become more active."}, {"duration": 3.847, "start": 422.54, "text": "And similar to the weight changes, you're going to get the most bang for your buck"}, {"duration": 3.893, "start": 426.387, "text": "by seeking changes that are proportional to the size of the corresponding weights."}, {"duration": 2.956, "start": 432.14, "text": "Now of course, we cannot directly influence those activations,"}, {"duration": 2.384, "start": 435.096, "text": "we only have control over the weights and biases."}, {"duration": 3.355, "start": 437.48, "text": "But just as with the last layer, it's helpful to"}, {"duration": 3.285, "start": 440.835, "text": "keep a note of what those desired changes are."}, {"duration": 2.358, "start": 444.58, "text": "But keep in mind, zooming out one step here, this"}, {"duration": 2.262, "start": 446.938, "text": "is only what that digit 2 output neuron wants."}, {"duration": 4.182, "start": 449.76, "text": "Remember, we also want all the other neurons in the last layer to become less active,"}, {"duration": 3.247, "start": 453.942, "text": "and each of those other output neurons has its own thoughts about"}, {"duration": 2.411, "start": 457.189, "text": "what should happen to that second to last layer."}, {"duration": 4.701, "start": 462.7, "text": "So, the desire of this digit 2 neuron is added together with the desires"}, {"duration": 5.55, "start": 467.401, "text": "of all the other output neurons for what should happen to this second to last layer,"}, {"duration": 3.264, "start": 472.951, "text": "again in proportion to the corresponding weights,"}, {"duration": 4.505, "start": 476.215, "text": "and in proportion to how much each of those neurons needs to change."}, {"duration": 3.88, "start": 481.6, "text": "This right here is where the idea of propagating backwards comes in."}, {"duration": 3.657, "start": 485.82, "text": "By adding together all these desired effects, you basically get a"}, {"duration": 3.883, "start": 489.477, "text": "list of nudges that you want to happen to this second to last layer."}, {"duration": 3.627, "start": 494.22, "text": "And once you have those, you can recursively apply the same process to the"}, {"duration": 2.793, "start": 497.847, "text": "relevant weights and biases that determine those values,"}, {"duration": 3.431, "start": 500.64, "text": "repeating the same process I just walked through and moving backwards"}, {"duration": 1.029, "start": 504.071, "text": "through the network."}, {"duration": 4.103, "start": 508.96, "text": "And zooming out a bit further, remember that this is all just how a single"}, {"duration": 3.937, "start": 513.063, "text": "training example wishes to nudge each one of those weights and biases."}, {"duration": 2.8, "start": 517.48, "text": "If we only listened to what that 2 wanted, the network would"}, {"duration": 2.94, "start": 520.28, "text": "ultimately be incentivized just to classify all images as a 2."}, {"duration": 5.184, "start": 524.06, "text": "So what you do is go through this same backprop routine for every other training example,"}, {"duration": 4.193, "start": 529.244, "text": "recording how each of them would like to change the weights and biases,"}, {"duration": 2.563, "start": 533.437, "text": "and average together those desired changes."}, {"duration": 4.163, "start": 541.72, "text": "This collection here of the averaged nudges to each weight and bias is,"}, {"duration": 4.221, "start": 545.883, "text": "loosely speaking, the negative gradient of the cost function referenced"}, {"duration": 3.576, "start": 550.104, "text": "in the last video, or at least something proportional to it."}, {"duration": 4.01, "start": 554.38, "text": "I say loosely speaking only because I have yet to get quantitatively precise"}, {"duration": 3.904, "start": 558.39, "text": "about those nudges, but if you understood every change I just referenced,"}, {"duration": 2.533, "start": 562.294, "text": "why some are proportionally bigger than others,"}, {"duration": 4.063, "start": 564.827, "text": "and how they all need to be added together, you understand the mechanics for"}, {"duration": 2.11, "start": 568.89, "text": "what backpropagation is actually doing."}, {"duration": 4.269, "start": 573.96, "text": "By the way, in practice, it takes computers an extremely long time to add"}, {"duration": 4.211, "start": 578.229, "text": "up the influence of every training example every gradient descent step."}, {"duration": 1.68, "start": 583.14, "text": "So here's what's commonly done instead."}, {"duration": 3.446, "start": 585.48, "text": "You randomly shuffle your training data and then divide it into a whole"}, {"duration": 3.494, "start": 588.926, "text": "bunch of mini-batches, let's say each one having 100 training examples."}, {"duration": 3.26, "start": 592.94, "text": "Then you compute a step according to the mini-batch."}, {"duration": 3.052, "start": 596.96, "text": "It's not going to be the actual gradient of the cost function,"}, {"duration": 3.199, "start": 600.012, "text": "which depends on all of the training data, not this tiny subset,"}, {"duration": 2.264, "start": 603.211, "text": "so it's not the most efficient step downhill,"}, {"duration": 4.184, "start": 605.475, "text": "but each mini-batch does give you a pretty good approximation, and more importantly,"}, {"duration": 2.461, "start": 609.659, "text": "it gives you a significant computational speedup."}, {"duration": 4.258, "start": 612.82, "text": "If you were to plot the trajectory of your network under the relevant cost surface,"}, {"duration": 4.412, "start": 617.078, "text": "it would be a little more like a drunk man stumbling aimlessly down a hill but taking"}, {"duration": 4.309, "start": 621.49, "text": "quick steps, rather than a carefully calculating man determining the exact downhill"}, {"duration": 4.361, "start": 625.799, "text": "direction of each step before taking a very slow and careful step in that direction."}, {"duration": 3.12, "start": 631.54, "text": "This technique is referred to as stochastic gradient descent."}, {"duration": 3.66, "start": 635.96, "text": "There's a lot going on here, so let's just sum it up for ourselves, shall we?"}, {"duration": 3.78, "start": 640.44, "text": "Backpropagation is the algorithm for determining how a single training"}, {"duration": 2.808, "start": 644.22, "text": "example would like to nudge the weights and biases,"}, {"duration": 3.024, "start": 647.028, "text": "not just in terms of whether they should go up or down,"}, {"duration": 3.726, "start": 650.052, "text": "but in terms of what relative proportions to those changes cause the"}, {"duration": 1.782, "start": 653.778, "text": "most rapid decrease to the cost."}, {"duration": 3.97, "start": 656.26, "text": "A true gradient descent step would involve doing this for all your tens of"}, {"duration": 3.97, "start": 660.23, "text": "thousands of training examples and averaging the desired changes you get."}, {"duration": 4.046, "start": 664.86, "text": "But that's computationally slow, so instead you randomly subdivide the"}, {"duration": 4.334, "start": 668.906, "text": "data into mini-batches and compute each step with respect to a mini-batch."}, {"duration": 3.863, "start": 674.0, "text": "Repeatedly going through all of the mini-batches and making these adjustments,"}, {"duration": 3.17, "start": 677.863, "text": "you will converge towards a local minimum of the cost function,"}, {"duration": 4.012, "start": 681.033, "text": "which is to say your network will end up doing a really good job on the training"}, {"duration": 0.495, "start": 685.045, "text": "examples."}, {"duration": 4.796, "start": 687.24, "text": "So with all of that said, every line of code that would go into implementing backprop"}, {"duration": 4.684, "start": 692.036, "text": "actually corresponds with something you have now seen, at least in informal terms."}, {"duration": 2.921, "start": 697.56, "text": "But sometimes knowing what the math does is only half the battle,"}, {"duration": 3.639, "start": 700.481, "text": "and just representing the damn thing is where it gets all muddled and confusing."}, {"duration": 3.717, "start": 704.86, "text": "So for those of you who do want to go deeper, the next video goes through the same"}, {"duration": 3.536, "start": 708.577, "text": "ideas that were just presented here, but in terms of the underlying calculus,"}, {"duration": 3.808, "start": 712.113, "text": "which should hopefully make it a little more familiar as you see the topic in other"}, {"duration": 0.499, "start": 715.921, "text": "resources."}, {"duration": 3.498, "start": 717.34, "text": "Before that, one thing worth emphasizing is that for this algorithm to work,"}, {"duration": 3.543, "start": 720.838, "text": "and this goes for all sorts of machine learning beyond just neural networks,"}, {"duration": 1.519, "start": 724.381, "text": "you need a lot of training data."}, {"duration": 4.234, "start": 726.42, "text": "In our case, one thing that makes handwritten digits such a nice example is that there"}, {"duration": 4.086, "start": 730.654, "text": "exists the MNIST database, with so many examples that have been labeled by humans."}, {"duration": 3.904, "start": 735.3, "text": "So a common challenge that those of you working in machine learning will be familiar with"}, {"duration": 2.676, "start": 739.204, "text": "is just getting the labeled training data you actually need,"}, {"duration": 2.807, "start": 741.88, "text": "whether that's having people label tens of thousands of images,"}, {"duration": 2.413, "start": 744.687, "text": "or whatever other data type you might be dealing with."}], "video_id": "Ilg3gGewQ5U"}